	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">I dont know if I will ever have the time to finish this completely...so I am going to post it now.  Please keep in mind this is very rough and I haven't had time really to QC (quality check) it.  Also I took some liberties of names of NPCs since this is actually part of a longer story I am writing about the paladin.  I just changed this up to be set in the EQ instead of the world in my head.  Oh and also keep in mind that I am by no means a professional at this...it's a hobby and I don't think I have ever let anyone read anything I have written before (well except in HS but I had to or I would have failed) so please be gentle with me  <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt=""> .  I hope someone enjoys it....(oh and be prepared cuz it's looooooooooooong)<br />
<br />
<edit:  <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&postid=15911#post15911" target="_blank">Part 2</a> to the story has been added in my last post on this thread.  More liberties have been taken, particularly with spells.  I would also like to thank Fistel, Thorvyn and Dragdar for allowing me the use of their characters for this part of the story...hope I did them some justice <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="">><br />
<br />
<edit II:  <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&postid=16643#post16643" target="_blank">The End</a> of my little story has been posted.  I feel like I rushed through it because things have been pretty busy for me lately (Damn sicko virus makin people! hate you!  But that is for another time and place).  More thanks to Ventor and Uthan for use (though limitied sorry just didn't have the time to fully use them like I wanted to <img src="images/smilies/frown.gif" border="0" alt="">) of their characters.  Hope everyone enjoys this last installment.  Thanks for reading /salute!><br />
<br />
Part 1:  The Journey to the Great Divide<br />
<br />
Brushing the dust from his beard Gnarm stared wearily at the mountains ahead.  “Still two days journey to Thurgadin yet.  Best spend the night here where der ain’t any giants roamin round.”<br />
<br />
The small band gathered up their bloodied weapons and prepared to rest for the night...the journey had been long, and the thought of rest felt good to everyone.  They quickly prepared a meal over a small fire and set up watches for the night.<br />
<br />
The night quickly passed, too quickly as far as Gnarm was concerned, and the band was awoken by the sun gleaming off the fresh snow.  <br />
<br />
“We gonna be fightin some giants t’day friends, I can smell em.”  Gnarm smiled as he said this.  “Should be a good day!”  The thrill of the hunt could be seen in the stout dwarfs every move.  One hand unconsciously caressed the black mace at his hip while the other stoked the long braids of his golden blond beard.  The reflection of the morning sun was bright off his bald head and the wear of battle was evident in his cheeks.<br />
<br />
The group quickly set off towards the Great Divide, just beyond which Thurgadin lied, with its promises of dwarven stout and a warm bed.  The friends were quite anxious.  They did not foresee the darkness that awaited them.<br />
<br />
 __________________________________________________<br />
______________________<br />
<br />
“Gnarm Silverhand WILL DIE TODAY!”  Rockem Dwarfsmasher exclaimed.  Smashing his giant fist into the wooden table in front of him and sending his breakfast flying in several directions.  “First him and his friends then Thurgadin!”<br />
<br />
The Giant stood up from his chair and shifted his axe from his hip to his hand rubbed a scar that ran from across his chest.  “Release the wolves.”<br />
<br />
 __________________________________________________<br />
______________________<br />
<br />
“Over there” Loryann excitedly exclaimed. “That must be the Great Divide!”<br />
<br />
“Bout damn time.”  Gnarm mumbled into his beard.  The sun was fading into the horizon now, and the air was bitter cold.  The day had been clear and the traveling was swift.  But the night showed signs of snow and harsh winds.<br />
<br />
The five adventurers glared down on the Great divide from there perch on the mountain.  “This will be the most dangerous part of our Journey.  Keep you weapons nearby.”  The tall white haired human was staring down the horizon.  Two matching swords hanging from his hilt.  His shadow dancing along the mountain side the seven foot paladin platted the hilt of his swords…taking comfort in their presence.<br />
<br />
Bah!  Yer getting soft in yer old age Graydon!  What’s a few Frost Giants between friends!  Har har lets go have some fun!”  Gnarm exclaimed as he raced down the hill as fast as his short legs could move him.  Graydon noted the gleam in the Cleric’s eye…Gnarm meant not to avoid giants but to go straight at them…it was going to be a hard fight to Thurgadin for sure.  The friends quickly raced after their stocky, if not slightly crazed priest.<br />
<br />
“HALT!”  Loryann screamed just as they neared the Great Divide.<br />
<br />
Gnarm quickly jerked his head around, “Whaaaaaaaaa.”  The slick snow and quick stop causing him to loose his footing and the dwarf flipped head over heals into the snow.<br />
<br />
“Oh great Gnarm you’re not hurt are you? Ha ha!”  Loryann giggled.<br />
<br />
Gnarm pulled himself out of the snow and glared at the Halfing.  “If’n ye weren’t the best dern tracker in da north I’d toss ye off dat mountain lass!” <br />
<br />
“You would not!”  Loryann curtly responded.  Crossing her arms and snapping her head away from Gnarm.<br />
<br />
“Dern halflins!  Don’t ye have no manners?”<br />
<br />
“Darn Dwarfs!  Don’t you have any soap?”  Yelled the Ranger as she slipped behind Graydon.  Putting him between her and the unkempt dwarf.<br />
<br />
“Humph!  Soap overrated…less yer beard need a cleanin.”  Gnarm shook his fist at the Halfling, to which the Halfling quickly placed her thumbs in her ears and wiggled her fingers add the resounding “PPBBBTTT!” sound of a raspberry.<br />
<br />
“Enough! Why did you stop us Loryann?”  Graydon was growing tired of the dwarf and Halfling’s constant games.<br />
<br />
“Oh nothing just a few wolves attempting to surround us.”<br />
<br />
“By Brell’s Beard lass! Why didn’t ye say some…?”  His sentence cut short as a five hundred pound wolf barreled into him.  Gnarm could feel the beast’s teeth ripping into his arm.  Gnarm quickly grabbed the wolf by the collar with his shield hand and turned his body, using the momentum of the wolf to send it past him, tearing the wolf’s collar off in the process.  He could feel the wound in his arm bleeding, but ignored it.  “Brandish yer swords and spells it time ta kick some wolf arse!”  The dwarf’s words were filled with the glee of battle fury.<br />
<br />
“For the Glory of the Champions of Brell!”  Gnarm shouted as he lifted his mace and began an old Dwarven war song.  Using the song as a prayer to Brell, the power of his god filled him, making his muscles bulge and quickening his reactions.<br />
<br />
The wolf recovered and turned to face Gnarm.  Holding his head low he stalked the cleric, circling him waiting for the moment to pounce.  All around the adventurers wolfs sprang.  And the sound of battle quickly picked up a heavy pace.<br />
<br />
Gnarm quickly scanned the group, insuring his friends were holding up well, and the hulking wolf to that as an opening to pounce.  But Gnarm anticipated this and he quickly dropped to one knee.  The wolf leaping at Gnarm’s throat found only the cold steel of Gnarm’s shield.  A resounding thud went off as the wolf’s face slammed into the dwarfs shield, leaving his ribs exposed.  Gnarm quickly swung his mace with all his might, smashing the bewildered wolf sharply in ribs.  The force of the blow sunk deep and the mace began to glow as its magic activated.  The wolf shuttered and let out a pitiful yelp as Gnarm’s mace siphoned life from the wolf to heal its wielder.  The wolf fell to the ground and struggled to pull itself up, one of its front legs now useless.  Gnarm ran in with a follow up attack but the wolf was on the run now and Gnarm had no desire to chase.<br />
<br />
Gnarm surveyed the battle field.  Two wolves lay dead and the other two near there.  Aranthus, the wizard, kneeled next to the smoking remains of a wolf.  Initially he just looked tired but to Gnarm’s determined eye he could see that Aranthus was in severe pain.  Blood could be seen in several areas on his robe and from the corners of his mouth.  Gnarm made a hurried prayer to Brell and Aranthus wounds closed and light returned to his eyes as he was covered in a soft blue light.<br />
<br />
“By all that is holy lad, ye gotta speak up when yer being hurt!  I knows yer quiet an all but I can’t be watching ye all da dern time!”  Gnarm waggled his finger at Aranthus as he said this.<br />
<br />
“Behind you!”  Aranthus screamed in response.<br />
<br />
Gnarm quickly spun on his heels, searching his mind for the proper prayer.  The wolf had returned and was nearly on him again.  Gnarm shouted the words of his prayer and threw his hand forward spreading his fingers wide and the wolf came to a dead stop in mid run as if it had hit a brick wall.  Another final pitiful yelp escaped from the wolf as Loryann's arrow pierced its heart.<br />
<br />
“Hehe…thankey fer dat lad!”<br />
<br />
Gnarm wiped the sweat from his bald head and glanced down at the collar in his hand.  He tossed the object to the paladin.  “Heh…looks like someone knows we’re back Graydon.”<br />
<br />
Graydon glanced down at the collar and nodded, “Aye.”<br />
<br />
“Seems the trip to Thurgadin is gonna be more interesting den I first thought if da Dwarfsmasher Frosties be lookin fer our heads.”<br />
<br />
To Be Continued… <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&postid=15911#post15911" target="_blank">Part 2 Below!!</a> <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt=""> <a href="http://www.eqcleric.com/forums/showthread.php?s=&postid=16643#post16643" target="_blank">The End Below</a></font></p>
	
