	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">Part III:  The End part!<br />
<br />
Gnarm settled himself on top of a rock in front of the waterfall hiding the entrance to Thurgadin, watching the mighty giant’s storm towards him.  It was quiet now, but soon the morning sky would erupt with the sounds of battle and inevitably death.  Their plan was good but was it enough?  The odds were very much in the giants favor.  “I hope me fellow Brellians got da word in time.”  Gnarm muttered as he prayed to the Lord Underfoot for his blessings on the dwarves of Thurgadin and all that fought with them.  The giants grew near, the battle was at hand.  Gnarm solemnly finished his prayer and summoned up all of his inner strength to be strong for what was ahead.<br />
<br />
As Rockem decended on the waterfall, Rockem was surprised to see but one lone dwarf standing in his way.  The same dwarf that stood in his way 15 seasons ago, the same dwarf who was supposed to be dead by now.  Anger coursed through the giants veins and he halted the marching giants.<br />
<br />
“Gnarm Silverhand.  We meet again foul dwarf.”<br />
<br />
Standing on top of his chosen rock, his divine maul resting on his shoulder.  Gnarm took up the most arrogant posture a dwarf could take, forcing the fear that he knew showed in his face out as best he could.  “Aye fer one last time.”<br />
<br />
“Even you cannot stop me fool.  This time it we who are stronger!”<br />
<br />
“Turn back now Rockem or be responsible fer what comes of it.  Oh aye, ye may win t’day frostie, but ya will not be celebratin.  I warn ye now, by decree of da Great Lord Underfoot, for every dwarf, gnome an halfing dat die t’day a year of hardship will fall on the Frost Giants of the great divide, courtesy of Brell’s Champions.  We will hunt every frost giant on Norrath until yer race is but a tale told by old men to da children of his clan.  We ave tolerated ye fer long enough giant.  If ye throw one stone at the walls of Thurgadin you doom your race.”<br />
<br />
Gnarm knew the giant would not turn around, just the opposite, he hoped to anger the giant into a charge.  Hopefully creating the opening needed for the Thurgadin to prevail.  Gnarm silently prayed that his fellow Champions of Brell were on their way and would make it in time, for without there help it was doubtful Thurgadin would survive the day.  <br />
<br />
Rockem’s face gleemed red with anger.  “Kill the dwarf!”  And on his order hundreds of rocks flew in the direction of the exposed dwarf, just as Gnarm had hoped.  Quickly calling upon Brell Gnarms body was covered in a soft white glow just as the first rock plowed into his chest…and bounced harmlessly away.  Rock after rock pounded into the dwarf and each one fell away like the first leaving the dwarf unharmed and unmoved.<br />
<br />
“You cannot win frostie, for we are protected by Brell!”  Gnarm feigned a laugh as best he could.  He knew he had but a precious few seconds left to force the giants to charge.<br />
<br />
Almost on cue Rockem drew his mighty axe and signaled the charge and the rest of the giants stormed towards the entrance to Thurgadin.  Before the first wave had made ten paces an explosion of arrows, bolts and flung hammers came from till now expertly hidden dwarves and a halfing.  The battle for Thurgadin had now begun.  Out from every tree, every rock and every hole a dwarf crawled calling to their god for victory.  Startled by the sudden counter attack the giants ranks divided, attempting to engage at all points, the suddenly plentiful dwarves.<br />
<br />
Graydon leaped from his hiding place, high in a tree, landing on the nearest unsuspecting Giant and sending his sword deep into the surprised giants chest.  “The first kill is always the easiest” the paladin thought as he leaped away from the falling giant and turned to engage another.  His blades hummed as they sliced through the air and through giant flesh with equal ease.  He was lost now, lost in the fury of battle, every swing was smooth and calculated, instinct and years and years of fighting took over his every move.  The giant swung is axe at the paladin’s head expecting to muscle through the humans weak parry attempt.  The giant was quite surprised when the “weak” human deflected the blow and countered with his other blade, slicing the tendons above the giants kneecaps and sending the brute sprawling into the cold earth.  As one the giant fell two more moved in.<br />
<br />
Gnarm watched over the battle field aside his fellow priests.  Hoping his surprise was enough to hold the giants back till reinforcements came.  The initial shock had worn off now and the defenders had moved in a semicircle formation around the clerics.  Standing shoulder to shoulder just trying to keep the giants at bay.  If a dwarf fell another quickly took his place.  The line was holding and Gnarm meant to make it hold longer.  Reaching deep into his pouch he pulled out four small gleaming red stones.  Beautiful and with them great divine powers could be unleashed.  Gnarm placed to stones in each hand, then raised them to the heavens, chanting a prayer.  He voice boomed across the Great Divide and through the walls of Thurgadin as he called upon Brell.  The last words of the spell echoed through the divide and the battlefield was bathed in a blue light.  Gnarm staggered and fell to a knee his mind sapped of all its strength, but the spell was working, his allies fighting the giants defected blows they should not have been able to, and took only wounds from blows that should have cut them in half.  <br />
<br />
The priests around Gnarm worked meticulously to keep those doing battle healed.  Healing light constantly bathed the battle field.  But even with these Clerics working their powerful prayers dwarves still fell, and Gnarm knew that as soon as one section broke that the giants would go right after the vulnerable priests.  Having exhausted his mind and unable to concentrate enough to remember a prayer, Gnarm picked up his maul and waited for the first giant to storm the priests.<br />
<br />
Above the battle Aranthus and Fistel floated watching and striking down any giant who broke the dwarven line.  Combining their gifts to confuse then smite the unsuspecting giants with fire, ice and magical energies.  For now the dwarves held well but with each passing second another hole would open.<br />
<br />
“There!”  Aranthus shouts, pointing in the northern part of the dwarven line.  Fistel fervently utters his enchantment freezing the giant who broke the line in his tracks.  Aranthus quickly followed with his most powerful fire incantation blasting the giant onto his back.  Another giant broke though on the eastern side and duo quickly turned to him, Fistel again unleashing his mind scrambling magic, starting to feel the exhaustion that comes with casting such powerful magics.  He fought it off the confusion as best and tried to concentrate on his task.  Aranthus began to recite to words to kill the confused giant, as he neared the end of his spell a large rock from below struck him in the head sending him sprawling.  Fistel’s spine shivered at sickening sound the rock made as it connected with the half-elves head.  His levitation spell still up Aranthus laid in a heap slowly descending towards the battlefield.  <br />
<br />
Graydon felt it, he knew his son was dead.  His neck broken from the force of the giant’s boulder.  The paladin had known loss before, it was part of the life, but this was different, this was his son.  The normally level headed knight’s heart filled with rage and his battle fury turned into a frenzy.  He no longer felt the pain of his wounds, no they were but a distraction, he had no time for distractions, he would make the giants pay.  His swords exploded into a flurry of movement parrying attacks and slashing through giant flesh.  But for every giant he felled two would take it’s place.  There were too many.<br />
<br />
The frezy left him as a giant struck him with a vicious gash to his chest, knocking the knight to the ground, his life blood spilling freely into the snow.  The pain was back…that excruciating pain that prevents any coherent thought.  Graydon forced all of his will into thoughts of his beloved son summoning all of his mental strength.  Struggling to move the crippled paladin placed his hand upon his wound and called upon his god, putting all his focus upon being healed.  What was a only a brief few seconds seemed to be minutes to the paladin as his healing power washed though him closing the gash on his chest and removing most of his pain.  Refreshed he stood and flashed his blades at his enemies…the gleam of frenzy again in his eyes.  The giants, once again, began to fall at the mighty paladin’s feet.<br />
<br />
Gnarm saw none of this, he only saw Rockem, headed straight for him.  The mighty frost giant had broken the dwarven line easily and had ensured he would not be blasted by the devil half-elf.  He would finally have his vengeance upon the dwarf who had thwarted his plans so many winters ago.  Rockem smiled as he thought these pleasant thoughts.<br />
<br />
The circle of defense around the clerics grew tighter and tighter by the second and Gnarm knew that time had just about run out.  An overwhelming feeling of sadness washed over him as he readied his mace to face the giant charging at him. “Let’s finish what we started so many years ago ya devil Giant!” Gnarm screamed as he charged at Rockem.<br />
<br />
“You army is defeated dwarf, now at last so are you!”<br />
<br />
Gnarm did not respond with words but with his maul.  Swinging it in a wide arc aimed at the giant’s hip.  Rockem parried the blow easily with his axe, grinning as he returned the attack to the dwarf.  Gnarm quickly ducked out of the way of the blow meant to chop off his head and rolled between the giants legs coming up behind his adversary.  The priests swing this time connected soundly smacking into the back of the giants leg.<br />
<br />
Rockem felt the blow and felt his leg jerk as it wanted to give out under the shier power of the hammer, but Rockem knew that would mean death and forced himself to stay standing.  He staggered forward and turned to again face the slippery dwarf.  Gnarm was an experienced giant hunter and Rockem knew it would not have ended with that first blow.  He raised his axe over his head and swung hard down at the pest.  Gnarm easily sidestepped the obvious attack right into the heel of Rockem’s boot sending the dwarf to the ground.<br />
<br />
“You are a dead dwarf now!”  Rockem shouted gleefully as he brought his axe down again at the dwarf.<br />
<br />
Gnarm tried to parry the axe but was disoriented.  He feel the cold steel bite deeply into his shoulder sending shots of pain up and down his body.  The dwarf knocked the axe away and rolled to his feet swinging his maul in a short quick arc at the giants hip.  Gnarm felt the power of the maul unleash as it connected with the giants him.  Gnarm smiled, “Bah!  I ain’t half dead yet, an I ain’t gonna die gaint der still 15 flavors o ale I ain’t tasted!”<br />
<br />
The giant cringed at the bite of the vicious hammer stumbling backwards.  His cut had hurt the dwarf he knew, but this dwarf would fight till all life was gone.  Rockem feigned a sweeping attack getting the dwarfs attention then swung his closed fist, connecting squarely with the dwarfs nose.  <br />
<br />
Gnarm stumbled backwards from the vicious strength of the blow, fighting back the wave of unconsciousness that tried to overcome him.  Before he could get his wits about him again he felt the steel axe sink into his side, breaking a rib and filling his body with pain.  The dwarf frantically knocked the axe away again with is his maul.  Pain was shouting at him from everywhere.  Spitting the blood from his mouth the dwarf charged back at the giant bringing his maul high over his head and throwing it at Rockem.<br />
<br />
Rockem’s smug confidence drained quickly as the dwarf’s maul smashed into his chest.  Sending a wave of uncontrollable pain through his body and knocking him off his feet.  The giant fought back the confusion and shock of the blow and moved to stand.  The pain from his chest and him shot through him and the giant let out a loud cry.  That’s when he saw the dwarf, maul again in hand, charging for another attack.  The giant scrambled to get to his feet but the dwarf was quicker connecting with a savage blow to the giants back.  Rockem’s back convulsed in pain and he again fell to the ground.  “Why do you not just DIE!”<br />
<br />
The dwarf stood over the crippled giant.  “Because giant I be a Champion of Brell and we fight with all our souls for da Lord Underfoot.  We will never just lie down defeated ta one such as ye.”  Gnarm did not see the other giant coming to help his master; he did not see the blow that struck him in the chest launching him off his feet.  He felt it though, and the subsequent crash into the snow.  The pain in his chest was excruciating and he was only half conscious as Rockem lifted him off his feet by his breast plate.<br />
<br />
Rockem stared at the beaten priest.  “You have met your end dwarf.  My kin have beaten back yours and we will soon march into Kaladim!”<br />
<br />
Gnarm stared at the giant, unable to move from the pain that wracked through his body.  ‘Is this how it would end?  At the hands of a worthless giant?  I suppose it is fitting…many of them have fallen to my spells and hammers through the years.’  The dwarf thought solemnly.  He forced the pain to the back of his mind and stared hard at the gaint, “You …”  Gnarm stopped and his eyes lit up as he saw something from behind the giant.  Off behind the battle field the air began to waver, or maybe flicker slowly.  Its pace increased till a bright flash of light filled the great divide…blinding dwarf and giant alike.  Gnarm quickly focused on the source blinking away the blindness…when he saw what was there a smile again showed on the weary dwarfs face and he stared again at Rockem. “…can kill me giant, but you have lost the battle for Thurgadin.”  Gnarm finished his statement by spitting in the giants eye.  “For the Underfoot Lord!”  Gnarm yelled as he felt the air rush by him, the result of being thrown by Rockem.  He felt the stone run into him at great speed, or did he run into it?  ‘The blackness was coming back now,’ he thought as he slumped to the floor, ‘Let it come, I am weary.’ The dwarf smiled as he closed his eyes and the darkness overcame him.<br />
<br />
The defenders of Kaladim all looked at the origin of the light, all fought away their blindness.  As the light receeded there stood a mighty army.  Dwarves, Halflings and Gnomes shoulder to shoulder glaring down on the battle field.  At there head Thorvyn Thunderfist and Dragdar Dragonblood sat on their mighty steeds.  The Champions Of Brell had arrived.  Dragdar raised his hammer and Thorvyn drew his sword and the shortest of the races charged into battle with the tallest.<br />
<br />
The Champions of Brell stormed the battle field spells blazing and weapons singing.  The downtrodden defenders gained new life and fought back against the giants with greater passion.  The giant army was pinned down between the defenders and Brell’s army…and the frost giant killing machine Paladin somewhere in the middle.<br />
<br />
Fistel saw he brothers and sisters arrive from his hiding spot, his mind had been to weak to concentrate.  So he took cover to rest and hopefully help more when his mind could channel a spell.  He also saw Gnarm crash into the rock cliff side that serves as the walls of Thurgadin and slump to the ground.<br />
<br />
“Oh dear Brell!”  Fistel exclaimed as he left his hiding spot and rushed to his friend.  When he got there he saw the beating Gnarm had taken…his armor was nearly in rags and blood was seemingly coming from everywhere.  Fistel jumped up as he saw the slightest breathing motion in the dwarfs chest, “You’re live you stubborn dwarf!  I must find you a healer.”  With that the gnome chanted the words to his invisibility spell and raced off for help.<br />
<br />
Fistel scurries through the battlefield looking for someone to help, time was critical.  Coming upon the first ranks of Brellians he spotted someone to help.  <br />
<br />
Ventor Bloodforge was had just felled her first giant.  Ready to engage the next.  When she swung around startled by something.<br />
<br />
“Stop Ventor, Gnarm needs a healer now!”  Fistel remembered to keep his words spaced so he could be understood. “We need to get one and get to him quickly!”<br />
<br />
Ventor nodded and ran off coming back followed closely by Uthan Ironsides, a paladin with modest healing abilities.  “Lets go!”<br />
<br />
Fistel didn’t waste any time, he chanted the words of his spell making everyone invisible and they headed back to find Gnarm.  Dancing between battling shorties and giants the three made it to Gnarm to find Rockem and his kin standing over the broken dwarf.<br />
<br />
“Hey meat head!  Leave ‘im alone!”  Ventor shouted as she made a very unlady like gesture at the giants.<br />
<br />
The three giants swung to find there adversaries, but of course saw nothing.  Confused the giants looked back and forth while the three Brellians walked right past them to their friend.  Uthan quickly prayed and layed his hand on Gnarm sending his healing energies into the fallin priest, and becoming visible at the same time.  <br />
<br />
Gnarm shook and scrambled to his feet a confused look in his eyes.  “So dey kill giants in heaven too eh?  Dis gonna be more fun den I thought.”<br />
<br />
Ventor and Fistel appeared in front of the rather mislead dwarf.  “No fatty, you aren’t dead.”<br />
<br />
Gnarm shook his head as if too clear his mind and looked hard at Rockem.  “Well ifn I ain’t ded let’s get ta makin dem!” Gnarm stated as he charged at Rockem, Ventor and Uthan quickly following.  “I got da one wit da scar ye can take de otters.”<br />
<br />
Rockem cursed out loud as Gnarm again stood up.  “Damn dwarf!  Why do you not die!” Infuriated Rockem raised his axe to meet the charging dwarf.<br />
<br />
Gnarm reached down to his pouch and pulled another of his ‘toy’ hammers out.  Chanting the required prayer he flung it at Rockem.  This hammer, like the last, formed into a larger hammer as it reached Rockem and started swingin at the giant.  Rockem, thoroughly confused by this, swung his axe at the hammer connecting hard and breaking it into bits.<br />
<br />
“Ha what was that pathetic…GAHHH!”  the giants sentence ended in a scream of pain as Gnarm’s hammer connected with his knee, breaking it.<br />
<br />
“Distraction,” Gnarm stated as if Rockem should have known that.  Gnarm brought his hammer around in another powerful sweep, slamming it into the side of the prone giants head.  The resounding boom from the blow could be heard across the battle field.  And Rockem Dwarfsmasher slumped lifeless to the ground.<br />
<br />
“I now dub the ‘Smashedbydwarf’ stupid giant.”  Gnarm spit on Rockem’s corpse and surveyed the battle field.  The two henchmen turned tail as soon as their leader fell, Ventor and Uthan following chasing screaming about the giants being “cowardly elf lovers.”  The other giants were making being quickly beaten back now…their morale gone and their leader dead they could not keep organized against Thorvyn’s contingent of paladins and warriors and Dragdars mighty clerical powers.<br />
<br />
Thurgadin was safe again and the ale would flow tonight.  Gnarm walked over to Rockem’s body and took off the giants crown.  He inspected it, shrugged and tossed it at Fistel.  “Dat prolly why he was so smart, keep it friend an thankey.”  With that Gnarm raced to the front line to join the Brellians and the Defenders in defeating the giants.<br />
<br />
The next morning Gnarm was awakened by a loud banging on the door.  The startled dwarf shot out of bed then fell on the floor, still dizzy from the night before.  “Hold on one dern second!”  The dwarf shook his head and struggled through the hang over to the door.  Gnarm opened it to find his paladin friend Graydon waiting there for him.<br />
<br />
“We leave in one hour.”  The knight stated as he threw Gnarm some clean clothes.<br />
<br />
“Where we goin?”<br />
<br />
“To kill the giants.”<br />
<br />
“Which?”<br />
<br />
“All of them.”  Graydon stated as he walked down the halls of Thurgadin towards the exit from the city.<br />
<br />
“I ain’t never gonna get no sleep.”  The dwarf stated as he hurriedly prepared his things, “Dern humans always getting in trouble.”<br />
<br />
The four friend stood close to one another as they passed through the battle field, storing the memories away.  None knew what was ahead for them, but they took comfort in each other and prepared for whatever lied ahead.<br />
<br />
THE END</font></p>
	
